    {
      "id": "10cb2d1958f06adf5a4c2796b5dcd60bc52e2b26",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2013-02-20 03:00:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAny more activity happening here? Any replies for Alex' concern?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "19b78cd8b3cfcbc6d076a984cdc4cb5cce6074f1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-05 16:20:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nOleg, I think adding code to ensure only the \"ldd_params\" options are added is unnecessary complexity. AFAIK, non \"ldd_params\" (i.e. version, fsname, etc.) will be ignored so there is no harm in adding them to the string.\n\nUnless you feel strongly about filtering these out, I think it will only add code bloat without providing much of a practical benefit.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "34a0c37aee8d8a40941d0c3b3dc87dcb997fd3c6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-06 08:22:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nyes, at the moment it should work fine, but the question is what will happen when someone add a new generic parameter conflicting with params you pass...\n\nmy personal take on this is that the original design was driven by specific-to-zfs reasoning. while i do undersand the reasoning, i'd say that in general lustre parameters should be set/tuned by lustre utils. if it was the case, then the whole handling for parameters would be common for all, specific code would be trivial and we won't have potential issues in the future.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e92854c2604e0b0a453666dc2785c68ae3ef8ee7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 124,
        "name": "Prakash Surya",
        "email": "lists@prakashsurya.com",
        "username": "prakash"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-07 00:07:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI agree, the params _should_ be set/tuned _only_ by the lustre utils.           \nThe problem with that, is the lustre tools are not user friendly. Using         \nzfs get/set is a *much* easier to use interface for our admins. So,             \nuntil the utils are fixed to be \"better\" this isn't an option we'd like         \nto pursue.                                                                      \n                                                                                \nI'm willing to fix up this patch to meet your needs, but I'm not                \ncompletely sure where to go from here. I see two options:                       \n                                                                                \n   a) Filter out *known* options which are *not* ldd_params                     \n      (i.e. version, fsname, etc.). This would ensure these                     \n      are not passed into the ldd_params string. The                            \n      \"drawback\" being anything with LDD_PREFIX that is                         \n      *not* known will be passed as ldd_params.                                 \n                                                                                \n   b) Only pass in *known* options which *are* ldd_params. This                 \n      ensures everything in the ldd_params string is valid. The                 \n      drawback to this is if a new param is added, the mount util               \n      must be modified to understand the new param.                             \n                                                                                \nI don't think (b) is an option because that is what we had before, IIRC,        \nand that obviously did not work. If we do (a), then we run into the             \nproblem where a new option is added that conflicts with one of the ZFS          \ndataset parameters (i.e. data set has \"lustre:xyz=on\" which is ignored,         \nbut then the ldd_param adds support for \"xyz\" so it's no longer                 \nignored).                                                                       \n                                                                                \nIMO, option (a) is do-able and something I can add to the patch. I just         \nwant to make sure it will satisfy your needs before I work on it. Will          \nthat work? Or did you have something else in mind?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "393e5670d6c80680592ff479c34021819715a3e5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-07 01:20:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nI noticed one potential defect in this code returning everything in ldd_params, when previously I thought it was just a cosmetic issue.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
